1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:26,545
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodassam Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodassam Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodassam

2
00:00:27,367 --> 00:00:31,833
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:34,618 --> 00:00:41,567
So the next word I wanted to tackle was puja.

4
00:00:42,789 --> 00:00:50,118
So it translates as honour, worship, but perhaps the nicest is devotional attention.

5
00:00:50,618 --> 00:00:51,299
Rather like that.

6
00:00:52,646 --> 00:00:55,173
devotional attention.

7
00:00:55,194 --> 00:01:00,648
So it's an attention which is flavoured with devotion.

8
00:01:02,612 --> 00:01:08,748
Like metta is an attention flavoured with loving kindness or goodwill.

9
00:01:11,816 --> 00:01:28,061
And really, the puja is the other side of the practice, this, you know, the actual teachings themselves, and then we put that into this practice of vipassana, which is an investigation.

10
00:01:29,103 --> 00:01:36,254
But without metta, without devotion, it's sort of, the practice can lack a bit of juice, you know.

11
00:01:37,417 --> 00:01:38,418
It gets a bit dry.

12
00:01:39,498 --> 00:01:42,081
So this really is the language of the heart.

13
00:01:42,362 --> 00:01:45,325
It's the heart's involvement in the spiritual process.

14
00:01:46,147 --> 00:02:02,766
And it's words such as wonder and awe, praise, worship, which is a little bit out of use these days, but it's a very strong praise, isn't it?

15
00:02:03,960 --> 00:02:19,560
and joy, the joy of receiving the Dharma, the joy, even the sympathetic joy in the Buddha himself having attained this enlightenment.

16
00:02:20,760 --> 00:02:27,049
So those are the sorts of devotional emotions you might say.

17
00:02:29,155 --> 00:02:58,437
and you can see that this expresses itself through art through buildings, temples all spiritual art in that sense and in pictures sculptures, the great art of religious spiritual sculptures and there's a music chanting

18
00:02:59,664 --> 00:03:12,469
In our school, it would be this sort of chanting, which is not only memorizing the Buddha's words, it's about creating the peacefulness that goes with it.

19
00:03:14,794 --> 00:03:19,242
And that's why, even if you listen to Gregorian chant, it's always...

20
00:03:19,578 --> 00:03:22,521
on a level of peaceful.

21
00:03:23,002 --> 00:03:34,397
The emotions come, the joy and the awe and all that, but they're sort of stabilized or rooted in this peace or equanimity.

22
00:03:35,019 --> 00:03:42,969
So if you listen to plain chant, just keep listening to it, it actually creates within you this very deep ongoing peace.

23
00:03:44,536 --> 00:03:50,242
Then of course it got corrupted into polyphonic music and all that stuff.

24
00:03:50,263 --> 00:03:53,907
And the emotion started growing until you get to the romantics and it becomes silly.

25
00:03:54,968 --> 00:04:02,338
But if you stay with this original spiritual music, it's always this one line, you see.

26
00:04:03,159 --> 00:04:10,188
And if they are happy, it sort of just rises gently above the medium of equanimity.

27
00:04:13,156 --> 00:04:16,432
That's my own take on music.

28
00:04:17,779 --> 00:04:25,867
So all those things that we see are all part of the devotional aspect of our practice.

29
00:04:26,848 --> 00:04:30,192
So that when we come into a shrine room, you see, you've got a statue.

30
00:04:30,452 --> 00:04:40,163
These statues have a mudra, which means their particular attitude in which the Buddha is in.

31
00:04:40,182 --> 00:04:46,470
So this one is the concentration mudra, the jhana mudra, which is the mudra really of enlightenment.

32
00:04:47,125 --> 00:04:51,130
You get others with the hand up, which is the mudra of fearlessness.

33
00:04:52,033 --> 00:04:56,959
You get the varada, the mudra of offering, with the left hand offering things.

34
00:04:57,480 --> 00:05:02,389
You get the mudra where he seems to be holding a lotus, which is the mudra of teaching.

35
00:05:03,310 --> 00:05:12,745
And perhaps the most famous one, or the most regular one, is where he's touching the earth, which is just before his enlightenment, when

36
00:05:13,298 --> 00:05:18,706
he, as it were, overcomes the attack of Mara, which was basically doubt.

37
00:05:20,249 --> 00:05:20,810
Like, who was he?

38
00:05:21,891 --> 00:05:23,053
And what was he playing at?

39
00:05:23,173 --> 00:05:24,716
Why don't you just enjoy life?

40
00:05:24,857 --> 00:05:27,321
Who are you to try and work out this great mystery?

41
00:05:29,163 --> 00:05:30,526
And he grounded himself, you see.

42
00:05:31,367 --> 00:05:38,800
Interestingly enough, it was the perfection of generosity which gave him the strength to carry on.

43
00:05:40,146 --> 00:05:43,511
When you give, you see, it's the renunciation.

44
00:05:43,571 --> 00:05:49,117
So, in a sense, he's reminding himself that he's not only doing it for himself.

45
00:05:49,137 --> 00:05:50,377
So, those are your mudras.

46
00:05:50,677 --> 00:05:54,442
And, you know, the candles.

47
00:05:54,983 --> 00:05:56,605
So, there's always candles.

48
00:05:56,904 --> 00:05:57,805
The light, you see.

49
00:05:57,985 --> 00:06:03,512
So, remember that the light of a candle is symbolic of the understanding, the path of wisdom.

50
00:06:03,992 --> 00:06:05,334
It's heat, the path of love.

51
00:06:06,214 --> 00:06:08,617
So, you start with love as your basis.

52
00:06:09,204 --> 00:06:10,906
And the action of the flame, good works.

53
00:06:12,048 --> 00:06:20,961
So that's in your eightfold path, right understanding, right attitude, that's the lover, right speech, right action, right livelihood.

54
00:06:20,982 --> 00:06:23,625
So the flame is really one of the better and the best symbols.

55
00:06:24,687 --> 00:06:29,495
Incense usually refers to the perfume of good actions in your life.

56
00:06:30,235 --> 00:06:32,478
That's where it's symbolical.

57
00:06:33,403 --> 00:06:38,672
And the flowers always have an essence, impermanence.

58
00:06:40,855 --> 00:06:42,177
They rise and pass away.

59
00:06:46,083 --> 00:06:51,591
When it comes to bowing, remember, that's a very strong body language for surrender.

60
00:06:53,132 --> 00:06:58,040
That's one thing, but I mean it can be done out of gratitude, you see, or out of praise.

61
00:06:59,101 --> 00:07:02,567
Depends on what you want to put into the action.

62
00:07:03,408 --> 00:07:10,317
Even if you find it difficult to do it physically, you can do it at least within yourself, the yielding.

63
00:07:12,901 --> 00:07:20,353
And then you get the practice of walking around, circumambulation, you see, always keeping the object of veneration to your right.

64
00:07:21,254 --> 00:07:27,963
So even the Buddha said, before he died, is to create these stupas out of his ashes.

65
00:07:28,314 --> 00:07:56,415
and they were separated into the eight eight people wanted these ashes eight different groups and it was divided into these different groups and what is it what is a stupa it's a burial mound so if you think about when you visit the graves of your parents or your grandparents or whatever that's what you're doing you're just going there to perhaps to remember your relationship with them to thank them for it

66
00:07:57,509 --> 00:08:06,901
So when you're walking around a stupa, that's basically a devotional exercise, you see, just to remember the memory of the Buddha in remembrance of me.

67
00:08:09,043 --> 00:08:10,425
And they also did it with Bodhi trees.

68
00:08:11,726 --> 00:08:17,033
So remember, in the beginning, for about 500 years, there was no statue or picture of the Buddha.

69
00:08:17,052 --> 00:08:25,744
He was always represented either by a tree or a footprint or a seat, anything but the actual physical representations.

70
00:08:26,584 --> 00:08:44,812
this came about five years later with the Greeks they started one line of sculpture very beautiful Greek Adonises and down in south of India the Mathura which were begun then and then since then of course there's always been statues about

71
00:08:47,375 --> 00:08:58,335
And so, finally, the expression of this puja, of this honour, devotion, etc., leads, you see, it's a sort of, it's the heart's response to the practice.

72
00:08:59,677 --> 00:09:03,264
So that when we have faith, it's not just an intellectual ascent.

73
00:09:03,644 --> 00:09:08,352
I mean, that's how it's often described, especially through the Christian tradition, right?

74
00:09:08,434 --> 00:09:37,833
partly a sort of an intellectual acceptance there has to be the heart with it there has to be a certain feeling that this is where one wants to be because that's where you're rooted in your own you know within the heart base and so taking the refuges and precepts is a way of re-establishing your heart commitment to the practice you're doing and what is it that you're actually doing when you take refuges and precepts so the Buddha, Dharma, Sangha

75
00:09:38,100 --> 00:09:42,429
you're basically slowly making that the reference point of your life.

76
00:09:43,773 --> 00:09:47,120
That's what it is.

77
00:09:47,139 --> 00:09:50,506
So it's like these merry-go-rounds with these horses going up and down.

78
00:09:51,279 --> 00:09:55,506
So most people are jumping on these horses, going round and round and round.

79
00:09:55,547 --> 00:10:03,940
And you find that, and even now you may find, that there are certain things that you're doing in your life which, as it were, are disconnected.

80
00:10:04,660 --> 00:10:07,466
A lot of people do all sorts of things, but they're all disconnected.

81
00:10:07,485 --> 00:10:11,471
They don't have a sort of central reference point to which it all makes sense.

82
00:10:12,813 --> 00:10:17,861
So by taking refuge in a particular spiritual path,

83
00:10:18,347 --> 00:10:20,711
what that becomes is your reference point.

84
00:10:20,730 --> 00:10:24,395
So now everything in your life has to make sense to this reference point.

85
00:10:25,216 --> 00:10:29,003
And that's how it becomes integral, interconnected.

86
00:10:29,984 --> 00:10:34,750
And from that you get your deeper meaning as to why the hell we're living here in the first place.

87
00:10:37,193 --> 00:10:40,678
And that's what the Buddha, that's what taking refuge is actually means.

88
00:10:40,818 --> 00:10:46,025
So it's not just an intellectual thing or even something that comes through vipassana practice.

89
00:10:46,663 --> 00:10:50,649
Actually, something which moves at a deeper level within the heart.

90
00:10:52,572 --> 00:11:02,684
And then, of course, one finds these practices, such as chanting and doing these circumambulations and all that.

91
00:11:02,705 --> 00:11:04,386
I mean, that's why we're having a stupor put in.

92
00:11:06,610 --> 00:11:07,851
You find them really uplifting.

93
00:11:08,172 --> 00:11:10,274
They're the juice of the practice, you might say.

94
00:11:14,238 --> 00:11:31,019
But, of course, none of it actually, I mean, and this is the other thing, then, of course, if your practice just becomes that, just becomes puja, then really there's no hope, because that's when the spiritual life corrupts into schmaltz.

95
00:11:33,543 --> 00:11:41,712
So it's got to be this balance, and it's got to be seen that the puja is there to support the practice of insight, not the other way around.

96
00:11:47,481 --> 00:11:50,890
I can only hope my few words have been of some assistance.

97
00:11:51,312 --> 00:12:01,018
May you be liberated from all your suffering sooner rather than later.

